e\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, H\u2082-saturated fluid\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 adsorbs onto the Fe\u2083S\u2084 surface at catalytic [Fe\u2084S\u2084]-like cluster sites. H\u2082 dissociates on the mineral surface providing hydride equivalents. Two-electron reduction of CO\u2082 yields formate (HCOO\u207b) via a surface-bound formylate intermediate. The reaction is thermodynamically favorable under the high H\u2082 fugacity and alkaline conditions of serpentinization-driven vents.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Roldan et al. (2015) demonstrated that greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084) catalyzes CO\u2082 reduction to formate under hydrothermal conditions, drawing analogy to the [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters in acetogenic CO\u2082 fixation. Preiner et al. (2020) confirmed that native iron and iron-sulfur minerals in serpentinization settings reduce CO\u2082 to formate, pyruvate, and other organics at 100\u00b0C under modest H\u2082 pressures. This is the first committed step of hydrothermal carbon fixation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Reverse water-gas shift reaction on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"450-550K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-300 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"higher temperature black smoker or subseafloor hydrothermal regime\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 CO + H\u2082O. At elevated temperatures on magnetite surfaces, the reverse water-gas shift equilibrium favors CO production. Magnetite provides the Fe\u00b2\u207a/Fe\u00b3\u207a redox couple that facilitates electron transfer. CO desorbs from the mineral surface and becomes available for Fischer-Tropsch-type and carbonylation reactions downstream.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The reverse water-gas shift reaction is well established in heterogeneous catalysis on iron oxide surfaces (Seewald et al., 2006). In hydrothermal systems, magnetite formed during serpentinization catalyzes this reaction at temperatures above ~200\u00b0C. McCollom & Seewald (2007) demonstrated CO production from CO\u2082/H\u2082 mixtures in hydrothermal experiments. CO is a critical C1 intermediate for subsequent Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate reduction to formaldehyde on native iron\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe\u2070)\", \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"native iron (Fe\u2070) with magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"reducing conditions, H\u2082-rich, awaruite (Ni\u2083Fe) may also contribute\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate is further reduced on native iron surfaces. Fe\u2070 acts as a strong two-electron reductant, donating electrons to reduce the carboxylate of formate to the aldehyde oxidation state. The surface-bound formate loses one oxygen (as water), yielding formaldehyde which desorbs into solution. The reaction is driven by the highly reducing potential of Fe\u2070 (E\u00b0 ~ -0.44 V).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Preiner et al. (2020) showed that native iron and awaruite in serpentinization settings can drive sequential CO\u2082 reduction through formate to more reduced C1 species including formaldehyde. Muchowska et al. (2017) demonstrated that Fe\u2070 powder can reduce carboxylate groups under mild aqueous conditions. While formaldehyde is thermodynamically unstable and short-lived in hydrothermal fluids, its continuous production maintains a low steady-state concentration sufficient for downstream reactions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type CO hydrogenation to formaldehyde on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-300 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Fischer-Tropsch type conditions, CO/H\u2082 mixtures\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO adsorbs onto magnetite surface Fe sites, forming a surface carbonyl species. Dissociative H\u2082 adsorption provides atomic hydrogen. Sequential hydrogenation of the surface-bound CO produces a formyl intermediate (HCO*) and then formaldehyde (H\u2082CO), which desorbs. This is the initial step of Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, with formaldehyde as the first stable oxygenated product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"McCollom et al. (1999) and Holm & Charlou (2001) reported Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis of organic compounds in hydrothermal systems on magnetite catalysts. FTT synthesis on magnetite at 400-500K produces C1-C3 oxygenated compounds including formaldehyde, methanol, and formic acid. Rushdi & Simoneit (2001) demonstrated FTT production of oxygenated species at comparable conditions. Formaldehyde is a key initial product of CO hydrogenation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis of aminoacetonitrile from formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mildly alkaline evaporitic pool, pH 7-9, dilute HCN and NH\u2083\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The Strecker synthesis proceeds via: (1) Nucleophilic addition of NH\u2083 to formaldehyde yields an amino alcohol (aminomethanol, HOCH\u2082NH\u2082). (2) Dehydration gives the imine (methanimine, CH\u2082=NH). (3) Nucleophilic addition of CN\u207b (from HCN) to the imine carbon yields aminoacetonitrile (H\u2082NCH\u2082CN). Montmorillonite clay surfaces concentrate the reactants in interlayer galleries and catalyze the condensation steps by providing Lewis acid sites.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker synthesis is the classical prebiotic route to amino acids, first proposed by Miller (1957) as the mechanism operating in spark discharge experiments. Cleaves et al. (2008) demonstrated Strecker synthesis under plausible prebiotic conditions. Ferris et al. (1996) showed montmorillonite catalyzes condensation reactions relevant to amino acid synthesis. The Strecker mechanism was confirmed by isotope labeling studies to be the dominant pathway in Miller-type experiments (Johnson et al., 2008).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin formation: formaldehyde + HCN \u2192 glycolonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"280-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mildly basic pH 7-9, tidal pool or evaporitic setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic addition of cyanide ion (CN\u207b) to the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of formaldehyde produces the cyanohydrin glycolonitrile (HOCH\u2082CN). The reaction is rapid and thermodynamically favorable at ambient temperatures. At pH 7-9, sufficient CN\u207b exists in equilibrium with HCN (pKa 9.2). Montmorillonite surfaces concentrate both species and may provide Lewis acid activation of the aldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glycolonitrile formation from HCN and formaldehyde is a well-known, rapid reaction in aqueous solution (Schlesinger & Miller, 1973). This cyanohydrin is a key intermediate in both the Kiliani-Fischer sugar synthesis pathway and in alternative routes to aminoacetonitrile. Patel et al. (2015) identified glycolonitrile as a crucial branch point in the Sutherland cyanosulfidic network. It is produced quantitatively at room temperature from equimolar HCN and HCHO.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Ammonolysis of glycolonitrile to aminoacetonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"NH\u2083-rich solution, pH 8-10, evaporitic pool with wet-dry cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia displaces the hydroxyl group of glycolonitrile via nucleophilic substitution at the carbon bearing the OH group. The reaction proceeds through an SN2-like mechanism: NH\u2083 attacks the CH\u2082 carbon, displacing OH\u207b to form aminoacetonitrile (H\u2082NCH\u2082CN). Alternatively, glycolonitrile first dehydrates to cyanomethylene which is then aminated. Montmorillonite surfaces facilitate the displacement by adsorbing glycolonitrile in favorable orientations.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction provides an alternative route to aminoacetonitrile that separates the cyanohydrin and amination steps of the Strecker synthesis. Schlesinger & Miller (1973) demonstrated that aminoacetonitrile can be formed from glycolonitrile and ammonia under prebiotic conditions. This stepwise route is important because it allows aminoacetonitrile to form even when HCN, HCHO, and NH\u2083 are not simultaneously present \u2014 glycolonitrile can accumulate first and react with NH\u2083 later during concentration events.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Partial hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile to glycinamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite, mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"neutral to mildly acidic pH, warm evaporitic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The nitrile group (C\u2261N) of aminoacetonitrile undergoes nucleophilic addition of water. A water molecule attacks the electrophilic nitrile carbon, producing an iminol intermediate which tautomerizes to glycinamide (H\u2082NCH\u2082CONH\u2082). This is the first hydrolysis step and is rate-limiting relative to the subsequent amide hydrolysis. Mineral surfaces catalyze the reaction by Lewis acid activation of the nitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis to amides is a well-characterized reaction in prebiotic chemistry. Commeyras et al. (2002) demonstrated that aminoacetonitrile hydrolysis proceeds stepwise through glycinamide. The nitrile-to-amide conversion is slower than amide-to-acid, making glycinamide a detectable intermediate. Mineral-catalyzed nitrile hydrolysis is documented by Rimola et al. (2007) who showed that clay surfaces lower the activation barrier via Lewis acid coordination to the nitrile nitrogen.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Glycinamide hydrolysis to glycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"warm prebiotic pool, neutral pH, may be accelerated by divalent metal cations (Zn\u00b2\u207a, Cu\u00b2\u207a)\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The amide bond of glycinamide undergoes hydrolysis: water attacks the carbonyl carbon of the amide, forming a tetrahedral intermediate which collapses to release NH\u2083 and yield glycine (H\u2082NCH\u2082COOH). The reaction is spontaneous in warm aqueous solution but slow; it is accelerated by elevated temperature, divalent metal ions, and mildly acidic or basic conditions. This step regenerates NH\u2083, which can be recycled into upstream Strecker or amination reactions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Amide hydrolysis to free amino acids is the terminal step of the Strecker synthesis. Bada et al. (1995) measured hydrolysis rates of simple amides under prebiotic conditions, showing half-lives of days to weeks at 80\u00b0C. The regeneration of NH\u2083 creates a partial autocatalytic loop. Commeyras et al. (2002) explicitly modeled glycinamide hydrolysis as the final step in prebiotic glycine formation, demonstrating plausible accumulation of glycine in warm pools.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ca(OH)\u2082 / borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mildly alkaline pH 9-11, formose-type reaction conditions, borate stabilization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Under alkaline conditions, formaldehyde undergoes a base-catalyzed aldol self-condensation. One HCHO molecule is deprotonated to form a carbanion-like enolate species, which attacks the carbonyl of a second HCHO molecule. The resulting aldol product is glycolaldehyde (HOCH\u2082CHO), the simplest aldose sugar. Borate minerals stabilize the product against further condensation by forming borate-diol complexes, preventing runaway polymerization (the 'formose problem').\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The formose reaction (Butlerov, 1861) producing glycolaldehyde from formaldehyde is catalyzed by Ca(OH)\u2082. Ricardo et al. (2004) demonstrated that borate minerals selectively stabilize specific sugar products including glycolaldehyde by forming borate esters, solving the long-standing problem of product selectivity in the formose reaction. Benner et al. (2012) further emphasized the role of borate in prebiotic sugar stabilization in evaporitic environments.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photo-oxidation of glycolaldehyde to glyoxylic acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"280-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO\u2082 (anatase) photocatalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (\u03bb < 300 nm), shallow tidal pool, no ozone shield\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV light (\u03bb < 300 nm) is absorbed by TiO\u2082 (anatase), generating electron-hole pairs. The photogenerated holes oxidize glycolaldehyde at the TiO\u2082 surface: the terminal CH\u2082OH group is oxidized to CHO, then to COOH, yielding glyoxylic acid (OHCCOOH). Alternatively, direct UV photolysis of glycolaldehyde in the Norrish Type I pathway cleaves the C-H bond of the aldehyde, followed by reaction with dissolved oxidants (e.g., HS\u207b-derived sulfur radicals).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (2012) showed UV-driven photoredox chemistry of simple sugars and aldehydes in prebiotic surface settings. TiO\u2082 is a known UV photocatalyst abundant in early Earth sediments (Cleaves & Miller, 1998). Glyoxylic acid is a key prebiotic \u03b1-keto acid identified by Eschenmoser (1999) as a central precursor to amino acids via reductive amination. The strong UV flux on the early Earth (no ozone layer) makes photochemical oxidation of alcohols to acids a plausible and efficient pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of glyoxylic acid to glycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"H\u2082-rich alkaline vent fluid, NH\u2084\u207a/NH\u2083 buffered, pH 8-10\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glyoxylic acid undergoes reductive amination on the greigite surface. (1) The aldehyde group of glyoxylic acid condenses with NH\u2083 to form an imine (Schiff base): OHCCOOH + NH\u2083 \u2192 HN=CHCOOH + H\u2082O. (2) The imine is reduced by H\u2082 (dissociated on the FeS\u2082/Fe\u2083S\u2084 surface) to yield glycine: HN=CHCOOH + H\u2082 \u2192 H\u2082NCH\u2082COOH. The mineral surface provides both the Lewis acid sites for imine formation and the reducing equivalents for hydrogenation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids is the prebiotic analog of transaminase biochemistry. Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003) demonstrated reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces under hydrothermal conditions. Muchowska et al. (2019) showed that glyoxylate undergoes reductive amination to glycine in the presence of iron and reducing agents, as part of a non-enzymatic proto-metabolic network. This represents the most metabolically relevant route to glycine, directly paralleling the reverse reaction of modern glycine dehydrogenase.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 Strecker glycine\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082 is reduced to formate on greigite in an alkaline hydrothermal vent, then further reduced to formaldehyde on native iron. Formaldehyde is transported to surface pools where it undergoes Strecker synthesis with HCN and NH\u2083 to form aminoacetonitrile, which is hydrolyzed through glycinamide to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO \u2192 Fischer-Tropsch formaldehyde \u2192 Strecker glycine\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082 is converted to CO via the reverse water-gas shift on magnetite at high temperatures. CO is hydrogenated to formaldehyde via Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite. Formaldehyde then enters the Strecker pathway in surface pools to yield glycine via aminoacetonitrile.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin \u2192 ammonolysis \u2192 glycine (glycolonitrile route)\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde reacts with HCN in a surface pool to form the cyanohydrin glycolonitrile. In a separate step, glycolonitrile reacts with NH\u2083 to produce aminoacetonitrile, which is hydrolyzed stepwise through glycinamide to glycine. This separates the C-C bond formation (cyanohydrin) from the C-N bond formation (amination).\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose \u2192 glyoxylate \u2192 reductive amination glycine\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde undergoes aldol self-condensation to glycolaldehyde in borate-stabilized alkaline pools. UV photo-oxidation on TiO\u2082 converts glycolaldehyde to glyoxylic acid. Glyoxylic acid is transported to hydrothermal vent settings where reductive amination on greigite with NH\u2083 and H\u2082 yields glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Full CO\u2082-formate-formaldehyde-formose-glyoxylate-glycine pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Complete pathway from CO\u2082 through hydrothermal formate and formaldehyde production, surface formose chemistry to glycolaldehyde, UV oxidation to glyoxylic acid, and hydrothermal reductive amination to glycine. This pathway crosses all three environments.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"CO\u2082 \u2192 CO \u2192 Fischer-Tropsch \u2192 formose \u2192 glyoxylate \u2192 glycine\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082 is converted to CO via reverse water-gas shift, then to formaldehyde via FTT synthesis on magnetite. Formaldehyde undergoes aldol condensation to glycolaldehyde, UV oxidation to glyoxylic acid, and hydrothermal reductive amination to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 glycolonitrile \u2192 glycine\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082 reduction yields formate, which is further reduced to formaldehyde. In surface pools, formaldehyde forms glycolonitrile with HCN, which is ammonolyzed to aminoacetonitrile and hydrolyzed to glycine. Combines hydrothermal C1 production with the stepwise cyanohydrin Strecker variant.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch formaldehyde \u2192 glycolonitrile \u2192 glycine\",\n      \"description\": \"CO (from reverse water-gas shift) is hydrogenated to formaldehyde via FTT synthesis. Formaldehyde enters the cyanohydrin pathway to glycolonitrile, then aminoacetonitrile, and finally glycine through stepwise hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface-only Strecker from prebiotically available formaldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Starting from formaldehyde already present in surface pools (e.g., from atmospheric photochemistry or meteoritic delivery), the direct Strecker synthesis with HCN and NH\u2083 yields aminoacetonitrile, hydrolyzed to glycine. Minimal pathway requiring no hydrothermal input.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface-only formose-glyoxylate from available formaldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Starting from formaldehyde already available in surface environments, aldol condensation yields glycolaldehyde, UV oxidation gives glyoxylic acid, and reductive amination produces glycine. This pathway bypasses the nitrile chemistry entirely, using aldol and redox chemistry instead.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_010\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_010\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde is the principal network hub. Two hydrothermal routes produce it (formate reduction, Fischer-Tropsch CO hydrogenation), and it feeds into three divergent surface pathways (Strecker, cyanohydrin, and formose aldol).\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"description\": \"Aminoacetonitrile is the convergence point for the two Strecker-type branches: the direct Strecker (rxn_005) and the stepwise glycolonitrile-ammonolysis route (rxn_007). Both feed into hydrolysis to glycine.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"description\": \"Ammonia participates in three reactions as a nucleophilic nitrogen source (Strecker, ammonolysis, reductive amination) and is regenerated by glycinamide hydrolysis, creating a partial autocatalytic cycle.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"description\": \"Glyoxylic acid is the convergence point for the non-Strecker route to glycine. It is produced by UV photo-oxidation of glycolaldehyde and consumed by hydrothermal reductive amination to glycine.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"description\": \"Glycine is the final convergence point (target molecule), synthesized by two mechanistically distinct terminal reactions: Strecker hydrolysis (rxn_009) and reductive amination (rxn_012).\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": []\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Glycine", "overall_strategy": "This network models 10 distinct prebiotic pathways to glycine spanning three environments. The strategy begins with hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction to C1 building blocks (formate, CO, formaldehyde) on iron-sulfur and iron-oxide mineral surfaces. These C1 intermediates are transported to surface environments where they undergo Strecker synthesis, cyanohydrin chemistry, and formose-type aldol condensation to produce glycine precursors (aminoacetonitrile, glyoxylic acid). Final hydrolysis and reductive amination steps yield glycine in both surface and biochemical settings. Formaldehyde serves as the principal hub molecule, linking hydrothermal carbon fixation to multiple divergent surface pathways. Aminoacetonitrile and glyoxylic acid serve as convergence points for the two major glycine-forming terminal reactions.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "formonitrile", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "oxidane", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CO", "iupac_name": "carbon monoxide", "common_name": "carbon monoxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO/c1-2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CHO2-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2H4N2", "iupac_name": "2-aminoacetonitrile", "common_name": "aminoacetonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4N2/c3-1-2-4/h1H2,(H2,2,4)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C2H2O3", "iupac_name": "oxoethanoic acid", "common_name": "glyoxylic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C2H3NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetonitrile", "common_name": "glycolonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H3NO/c3-1-2-4/h4H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetaldehyde", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "formamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C2H6N2O", "iupac_name": "2-aminoacetamide", "common_name": "glycinamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H6N2O/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H2,4,5)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C2H5NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminoacetic acid", "common_name": "glycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, H\u2082-saturated fluid"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 adsorbs onto the Fe\u2083S\u2084 surface at catalytic [Fe\u2084S\u2084]-like cluster sites. H\u2082 dissociates on the mineral surface providing hydride equivalents. Two-electron reduction of CO\u2082 yields formate (HCOO\u207b) via a surface-bound formylate intermediate. The reaction is thermodynamically favorable under the high H\u2082 fugacity and alkaline conditions of serpentinization-driven vents.", "reasoning": "Roldan et al. (2015) demonstrated that greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084) catalyzes CO\u2082 reduction to formate under hydrothermal conditions, drawing analogy to the [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters in acetogenic CO\u2082 fixation. Preiner et al. (2020) confirmed that native iron and iron-sulfur minerals in serpentinization settings reduce CO\u2082 to formate, pyruvate, and other organics at 100\u00b0C under modest H\u2082 pressures. This is the first committed step of hydrothermal carbon fixation."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Reverse water-gas shift reaction on magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006", "mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "450-550K", "pressure": "high (100-300 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "higher temperature black smoker or subseafloor hydrothermal regime"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 CO + H\u2082O. At elevated temperatures on magnetite surfaces, the reverse water-gas shift equilibrium favors CO production. Magnetite provides the Fe\u00b2\u207a/Fe\u00b3\u207a redox couple that facilitates electron transfer. CO desorbs from the mineral surface and becomes available for Fischer-Tropsch-type and carbonylation reactions downstream.", "reasoning": "The reverse water-gas shift reaction is well established in heterogeneous catalysis on iron oxide surfaces (Seewald et al., 2006). In hydrothermal systems, magnetite formed during serpentinization catalyzes this reaction at temperatures above ~200\u00b0C. McCollom & Seewald (2007) demonstrated CO production from CO\u2082/H\u2082 mixtures in hydrothermal experiments. CO is a critical C1 intermediate for subsequent Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Formate reduction to formaldehyde on native iron", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe\u2070)", "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "native iron (Fe\u2070) with magnetite", "aqueous": true, "other": "reducing conditions, H\u2082-rich, awaruite (Ni\u2083Fe) may also contribute"}, "mechanism": "Formate is further reduced on native iron surfaces. Fe\u2070 acts as a strong two-electron reductant, donating electrons to reduce the carboxylate of formate to the aldehyde oxidation state. The surface-bound formate loses one oxygen (as water), yielding formaldehyde which desorbs into solution. The reaction is driven by the highly reducing potential of Fe\u2070 (E\u00b0 ~ -0.44 V).", "reasoning": "Preiner et al. (2020) showed that native iron and awaruite in serpentinization settings can drive sequential CO\u2082 reduction through formate to more reduced C1 species including formaldehyde. Muchowska et al. (2017) demonstrated that Fe\u2070 powder can reduce carboxylate groups under mild aqueous conditions. While formaldehyde is thermodynamically unstable and short-lived in hydrothermal fluids, its continuous production maintains a low steady-state concentration sufficient for downstream reactions."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type CO hydrogenation to formaldehyde on magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (100-300 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Fischer-Tropsch type conditions, CO/H\u2082 mixtures"}, "mechanism": "CO adsorbs onto magnetite surface Fe sites, forming a surface carbonyl species. Dissociative H\u2082 adsorption provides atomic hydrogen. Sequential hydrogenation of the surface-bound CO produces a formyl intermediate (HCO*) and then formaldehyde (H\u2082CO), which desorbs. This is the initial step of Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, with formaldehyde as the first stable oxygenated product.", "reasoning": "McCollom et al. (1999) and Holm & Charlou (2001) reported Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis of organic compounds in hydrothermal systems on magnetite catalysts. FTT synthesis on magnetite at 400-500K produces C1-C3 oxygenated compounds including formaldehyde, methanol, and formic acid. Rushdi & Simoneit (2001) demonstrated FTT production of oxygenated species at comparable conditions. Formaldehyde is a key initial product of CO hydrogenation."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Strecker synthesis of aminoacetonitrile from formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_009", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": true, "other": "mildly alkaline evaporitic pool, pH 7-9, dilute HCN and NH\u2083"}, "mechanism": "The Strecker synthesis proceeds via: (1) Nucleophilic addition of NH\u2083 to formaldehyde yields an amino alcohol (aminomethanol, HOCH\u2082NH\u2082). (2) Dehydration gives the imine (methanimine, CH\u2082=NH). (3) Nucleophilic addition of CN\u207b (from HCN) to the imine carbon yields aminoacetonitrile (H\u2082NCH\u2082CN). Montmorillonite clay surfaces concentrate the reactants in interlayer galleries and catalyze the condensation steps by providing Lewis acid sites.", "reasoning": "The Strecker synthesis is the classical prebiotic route to amino acids, first proposed by Miller (1957) as the mechanism operating in spark discharge experiments. Cleaves et al. (2008) demonstrated Strecker synthesis under plausible prebiotic conditions. Ferris et al. (1996) showed montmorillonite catalyzes condensation reactions relevant to amino acid synthesis. The Strecker mechanism was confirmed by isotope labeling studies to be the dominant pathway in Miller-type experiments (Johnson et al., 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Cyanohydrin formation: formaldehyde + HCN \u2192 glycolonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "280-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": true, "other": "mildly basic pH 7-9, tidal pool or evaporitic setting"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic addition of cyanide ion (CN\u207b) to the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of formaldehyde produces the cyanohydrin glycolonitrile (HOCH\u2082CN). The reaction is rapid and thermodynamically favorable at ambient temperatures. At pH 7-9, sufficient CN\u207b exists in equilibrium with HCN (pKa 9.2). Montmorillonite surfaces concentrate both species and may provide Lewis acid activation of the aldehyde.", "reasoning": "Glycolonitrile formation from HCN and formaldehyde is a well-known, rapid reaction in aqueous solution (Schlesinger & Miller, 1973). This cyanohydrin is a key intermediate in both the Kiliani-Fischer sugar synthesis pathway and in alternative routes to aminoacetonitrile. Patel et al. (2015) identified glycolonitrile as a crucial branch point in the Sutherland cyanosulfidic network. It is produced quantitatively at room temperature from equimolar HCN and HCHO."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Ammonolysis of glycolonitrile to aminoacetonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": true, "other": "NH\u2083-rich solution, pH 8-10, evaporitic pool with wet-dry cycling"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia displaces the hydroxyl group of glycolonitrile via nucleophilic substitution at the carbon bearing the OH group. The reaction proceeds through an SN2-like mechanism: NH\u2083 attacks the CH\u2082 carbon, displacing OH\u207b to form aminoacetonitrile (H\u2082NCH\u2082CN). Alternatively, glycolonitrile first dehydrates to cyanomethylene which is then aminated. Montmorillonite surfaces facilitate the displacement by adsorbing glycolonitrile in favorable orientations.", "reasoning": "This reaction provides an alternative route to aminoacetonitrile that separates the cyanohydrin and amination steps of the Strecker synthesis. Schlesinger & Miller (1973) demonstrated that aminoacetonitrile can be formed from glycolonitrile and ammonia under prebiotic conditions. This stepwise route is important because it allows aminoacetonitrile to form even when HCN, HCHO, and NH\u2083 are not simultaneously present \u2014 glycolonitrile can accumulate first and react with NH\u2083 later during concentration events."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Partial hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile to glycinamide", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite, mineral surfaces", "aqueous": true, "other": "neutral to mildly acidic pH, warm evaporitic pool"}, "mechanism": "The nitrile group (C\u2261N) of aminoacetonitrile undergoes nucleophilic addition of water. A water molecule attacks the electrophilic nitrile carbon, producing an iminol intermediate which tautomerizes to glycinamide (H\u2082NCH\u2082CONH\u2082). This is the first hydrolysis step and is rate-limiting relative to the subsequent amide hydrolysis. Mineral surfaces catalyze the reaction by Lewis acid activation of the nitrile.", "reasoning": "Nitrile hydrolysis to amides is a well-characterized reaction in prebiotic chemistry. Commeyras et al. (2002) demonstrated that aminoacetonitrile hydrolysis proceeds stepwise through glycinamide. The nitrile-to-amide conversion is slower than amide-to-acid, making glycinamide a detectable intermediate. Mineral-catalyzed nitrile hydrolysis is documented by Rimola et al. (2007) who showed that clay surfaces lower the activation barrier via Lewis acid coordination to the nitrile nitrogen."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Glycinamide hydrolysis to glycine", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_015", "mol_003"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "warm prebiotic pool, neutral pH, may be accelerated by divalent metal cations (Zn\u00b2\u207a, Cu\u00b2\u207a)"}, "mechanism": "The amide bond of glycinamide undergoes hydrolysis: water attacks the carbonyl carbon of the amide, forming a tetrahedral intermediate which collapses to release NH\u2083 and yield glycine (H\u2082NCH\u2082COOH). The reaction is spontaneous in warm aqueous solution but slow; it is accelerated by elevated temperature, divalent metal ions, and mildly acidic or basic conditions. This step regenerates NH\u2083, which can be recycled into upstream Strecker or amination reactions.", "reasoning": "Amide hydrolysis to free amino acids is the terminal step of the Strecker synthesis. Bada et al. (1995) measured hydrolysis rates of simple amides under prebiotic conditions, showing half-lives of days to weeks at 80\u00b0C. The regeneration of NH\u2083 creates a partial autocatalytic loop. Commeyras et al. (2002) explicitly modeled glycinamide hydrolysis as the final step in prebiotic glycine formation, demonstrating plausible accumulation of glycine in warm pools."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Aldol condensation of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Ca(OH)\u2082 / borate minerals", "aqueous": true, "other": "mildly alkaline pH 9-11, formose-type reaction conditions, borate stabilization"}, "mechanism": "Under alkaline conditions, formaldehyde undergoes a base-catalyzed aldol self-condensation. One HCHO molecule is deprotonated to form a carbanion-like enolate species, which attacks the carbonyl of a second HCHO molecule. The resulting aldol product is glycolaldehyde (HOCH\u2082CHO), the simplest aldose sugar. Borate minerals stabilize the product against further condensation by forming borate-diol complexes, preventing runaway polymerization (the 'formose problem').", "reasoning": "The formose reaction (Butlerov, 1861) producing glycolaldehyde from formaldehyde is catalyzed by Ca(OH)\u2082. Ricardo et al. (2004) demonstrated that borate minerals selectively stabilize specific sugar products including glycolaldehyde by forming borate esters, solving the long-standing problem of product selectivity in the formose reaction. Benner et al. (2012) further emphasized the role of borate in prebiotic sugar stabilization in evaporitic environments."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "UV photo-oxidation of glycolaldehyde to glyoxylic acid", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "280-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO\u2082 (anatase) photocatalyst", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation (\u03bb < 300 nm), shallow tidal pool, no ozone shield"}, "mechanism": "UV light (\u03bb < 300 nm) is absorbed by TiO\u2082 (anatase), generating electron-hole pairs. The photogenerated holes oxidize glycolaldehyde at the TiO\u2082 surface: the terminal CH\u2082OH group is oxidized to CHO, then to COOH, yielding glyoxylic acid (OHCCOOH). Alternatively, direct UV photolysis of glycolaldehyde in the Norrish Type I pathway cleaves the C-H bond of the aldehyde, followed by reaction with dissolved oxidants (e.g., HS\u207b-derived sulfur radicals).", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (2012) showed UV-driven photoredox chemistry of simple sugars and aldehydes in prebiotic surface settings. TiO\u2082 is a known UV photocatalyst abundant in early Earth sediments (Cleaves & Miller, 1998). Glyoxylic acid is a key prebiotic \u03b1-keto acid identified by Eschenmoser (1999) as a central precursor to amino acids via reductive amination. The strong UV flux on the early Earth (no ozone layer) makes photochemical oxidation of alcohols to acids a plausible and efficient pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Reductive amination of glyoxylic acid to glycine", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_015", "mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "pyrite (FeS\u2082)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "H\u2082-rich alkaline vent fluid, NH\u2084\u207a/NH\u2083 buffered, pH 8-10"}, "mechanism": "Glyoxylic acid undergoes reductive amination on the greigite surface. (1) The aldehyde group of glyoxylic acid condenses with NH\u2083 to form an imine (Schiff base): OHCCOOH + NH\u2083 \u2192 HN=CHCOOH + H\u2082O. (2) The imine is reduced by H\u2082 (dissociated on the FeS\u2082/Fe\u2083S\u2084 surface) to yield glycine: HN=CHCOOH + H\u2082 \u2192 H\u2082NCH\u2082COOH. The mineral surface provides both the Lewis acid sites for imine formation and the reducing equivalents for hydrogenation.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids is the prebiotic analog of transaminase biochemistry. Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003) demonstrated reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces under hydrothermal conditions. Muchowska et al. (2019) showed that glyoxylate undergoes reductive amination to glycine in the presence of iron and reducing agents, as part of a non-enzymatic proto-metabolic network. This represents the most metabolically relevant route to glycine, directly paralleling the reverse reaction of modern glycine dehydrogenase."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Hydrothermal formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 Strecker glycine", "description": "CO\u2082 is reduced to formate on greigite in an alkaline hydrothermal vent, then further reduced to formaldehyde on native iron. Formaldehyde is transported to surface pools where it undergoes Strecker synthesis with HCN and NH\u2083 to form aminoacetonitrile, which is hydrolyzed through glycinamide to glycine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal CO \u2192 Fischer-Tropsch formaldehyde \u2192 Strecker glycine", "description": "CO\u2082 is converted to CO via the reverse water-gas shift on magnetite at high temperatures. CO is hydrogenated to formaldehyde via Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite. Formaldehyde then enters the Strecker pathway in surface pools to yield glycine via aminoacetonitrile.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Cyanohydrin \u2192 ammonolysis \u2192 glycine (glycolonitrile route)", "description": "Formaldehyde reacts with HCN in a surface pool to form the cyanohydrin glycolonitrile. In a separate step, glycolonitrile reacts with NH\u2083 to produce aminoacetonitrile, which is hydrolyzed stepwise through glycinamide to glycine. This separates the C-C bond formation (cyanohydrin) from the C-N bond formation (amination).", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_009", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Formose \u2192 glyoxylate \u2192 reductive amination glycine", "description": "Formaldehyde undergoes aldol self-condensation to glycolaldehyde in borate-stabilized alkaline pools. UV photo-oxidation on TiO\u2082 converts glycolaldehyde to glyoxylic acid. Glyoxylic acid is transported to hydrothermal vent settings where reductive amination on greigite with NH\u2083 and H\u2082 yields glycine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Full CO\u2082-formate-formaldehyde-formose-glyoxylate-glycine pathway", "description": "Complete pathway from CO\u2082 through hydrothermal formate and formaldehyde production, surface formose chemistry to glycolaldehyde, UV oxidation to glyoxylic acid, and hydrothermal reductive amination to glycine. This pathway crosses all three environments.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_012", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "CO\u2082 \u2192 CO \u2192 Fischer-Tropsch \u2192 formose \u2192 glyoxylate \u2192 glycine", "description": "CO\u2082 is converted to CO via reverse water-gas shift, then to formaldehyde via FTT synthesis on magnetite. Formaldehyde undergoes aldol condensation to glycolaldehyde, UV oxidation to glyoxylic acid, and hydrothermal reductive amination to glycine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_012", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Hydrothermal formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 glycolonitrile \u2192 glycine", "description": "CO\u2082 reduction yields formate, which is further reduced to formaldehyde. In surface pools, formaldehyde forms glycolonitrile with HCN, which is ammonolyzed to aminoacetonitrile and hydrolyzed to glycine. Combines hydrothermal C1 production with the stepwise cyanohydrin Strecker variant.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_009", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch formaldehyde \u2192 glycolonitrile \u2192 glycine", "description": "CO (from reverse water-gas shift) is hydrogenated to formaldehyde via FTT synthesis. Formaldehyde enters the cyanohydrin pathway to glycolonitrile, then aminoacetonitrile, and finally glycine through stepwise hydrolysis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_009", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Surface-only Strecker from prebiotically available formaldehyde", "description": "Starting from formaldehyde already present in surface pools (e.g., from atmospheric photochemistry or meteoritic delivery), the direct Strecker synthesis with HCN and NH\u2083 yields aminoacetonitrile, hydrolyzed to glycine. Minimal pathway requiring no hydrothermal input.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Surface-only formose-glyoxylate from available formaldehyde", "description": "Starting from formaldehyde already available in surface environments, aldol condensation yields glycolaldehyde, UV oxidation gives glyoxylic acid, and reductive amination produces glycine. This pathway bypasses the nitrile chemistry entirely, using aldol and redox chemistry instead.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_010"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_003", "mol_010"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_008", "description": "Formaldehyde is the principal network hub. Two hydrothermal routes produce it (formate reduction, Fischer-Tropsch CO hydrogenation), and it feeds into three divergent surface pathways (Strecker, cyanohydrin, and formose aldol).", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_010"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_009", "description": "Aminoacetonitrile is the convergence point for the two Strecker-type branches: the direct Strecker (rxn_005) and the stepwise glycolonitrile-ammonolysis route (rxn_007). Both feed into hydrolysis to glycine.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_005", "rxn_007"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_008"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_003", "description": "Ammonia participates in three reactions as a nucleophilic nitrogen source (Strecker, ammonolysis, reductive amination) and is regenerated by glycinamide hydrolysis, creating a partial autocatalytic cycle.