{"timestamp": "2026-03-17T19:58:55.543215", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.8\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: Glycine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: This network models 10 distinct prebiotic pathways to glycine spanning three environments. The strategy begins with hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction to C1 building blocks (formate, CO, formaldehyde) on iron-sulfur and iron-oxide mineral surfaces. These C1 intermediates are transported to surface environments where they undergo Strecker synthesis, cyanohydrin chemistry, and formose-type aldol condensation to produce glycine precursors (aminoacetonitrile, glyoxylic acid). Final hydrolysis and reductive amination steps yield glycine in both surface and biochemical settings. Formaldehyde serves as the principal hub molecule, linking hydrothermal carbon fixation to multiple divergent surface pathways. Aminoacetonitrile and glyoxylic acid serve as convergence points for the two major glycine-forming terminal reactions.\n\nMOLECULES (15 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (hydrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_003: NH3 (ammonia) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_004: HCN (hydrogen cyanide) [starting]\n  - mol_005: H2O (water) [starting]\n  - mol_006: CO (carbon monoxide) [intermediate]\n  - mol_007: CHO2- (formate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_008: CH2O (formaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_009: C2H4N2 (aminoacetonitrile) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_010: C2H2O3 (glyoxylic acid) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_011: C2H3NO (glycolonitrile) [intermediate]\n  - mol_012: C2H4O2 (glycolaldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_013: CH3NO (formamide) [intermediate]\n  - mol_014: C2H6N2O (glycinamide) [intermediate]\n  - mol_015: C2H5NO2 (glycine) [target]\n\nREACTIONS (12 nodes):\n  - rxn_001: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_007 (Hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction to formate on greigite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_002: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_006, mol_005 (Reverse water-gas shift reaction on magnetite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_003: mol_007, mol_002 -> mol_008 (Formate reduction to formaldehyde on native iron) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_004: mol_006, mol_002 -> mol_008 (Fischer-Tropsch-type CO hydrogenation to formaldehyde on magnetite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_005: mol_008, mol_004, mol_003 -> mol_009, mol_005 (Strecker synthesis of aminoacetonitrile from formaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_006: mol_008, mol_004 -> mol_011 (Cyanohydrin formation: formaldehyde + HCN \u2192 glycolonitrile) [Surface]\n  - rxn_007: mol_011, mol_003 -> mol_009 (Ammonolysis of glycolonitrile to aminoacetonitrile) [Surface]\n  - rxn_008: mol_009, mol_005 -> mol_014 (Partial hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile to glycinamide) [Surface]\n  - rxn_009: mol_014, mol_005 -> mol_015, mol_003 (Glycinamide hydrolysis to glycine) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_010: mol_008, mol_008 -> mol_012 (Aldol condensation of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_011: mol_012 -> mol_010 (UV photo-oxidation of glycolaldehyde to glyoxylic acid) [Surface]\n  - rxn_012: mol_010, mol_003, mol_002 -> mol_015, mol_005 (Reductive amination of glyoxylic acid to glycine) [Hydrothermal]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: Hydrothermal formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 Strecker glycine (5 steps)\n  - P2: Hydrothermal CO \u2192 Fischer-Tropsch formaldehyde \u2192 Strecker glycine (5 steps)\n  - P3: Cyanohydrin \u2192 ammonolysis \u2192 glycine (glycolonitrile route) (4 steps)\n  - P4: Formose \u2192 glyoxylate \u2192 reductive amination glycine (3 steps)\n  - P5: Full CO\u2082-formate-formaldehyde-formose-glyoxylate-glycine pathway (5 steps)\n  - P6: CO\u2082 \u2192 CO \u2192 Fischer-Tropsch \u2192 formose \u2192 glyoxylate \u2192 glycine (5 steps)\n  - P7: Hydrothermal formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 glycolonitrile \u2192 glycine (6 steps)\n  - P8: Fischer-Tropsch formaldehyde \u2192 glycolonitrile \u2192 glycine (6 steps)\n  - P9: Surface-only Strecker from prebiotically available formaldehyde (3 steps)\n  - P10: Surface-only formose-glyoxylate from available formaldehyde (3 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_008, mol_009, mol_003, mol_010\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 5\n\n\nPlease evaluate the network and respond with JSON:\n{\n    \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"<id>\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.85, ...},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"environmental_progression\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"target_achievement\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"feedback\": \"<pathway-specific feedback>\",\n            \"approved\": <true if confidence >= 0.8>,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_ids with issues\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"improvements\"]\n        }\n    ],\n    \"best_pathway_id\": \"<id of best pathway>\",\n    \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n    \"network_feedback\": \"<overall assessment>\",\n    \"approved\": <true if any pathway approved>,\n    \"hub_quality\": <0.0-1.0>,\n    \"convergence_quality\": <0.0-1.0>\n}\n", "raw_response": "{\n    \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.90, \"rxn_003\": 0.65, \"rxn_005\": 0.92, \"rxn_008\": 0.85, \"rxn_009\": 0.90},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.84,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.90,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.93,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.92,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.88,\n            \"feedback\": \"Classic and well-supported route. CO\u2082 reduction to formate on greigite is well-demonstrated (Preiner et al. 2020). The weakest step is formate reduction to formaldehyde on native iron (rxn_003), which is thermodynamically uphill and requires strong reducing conditions. The Strecker segment is textbook prebiotic chemistry. Environmental flow (Hydrothermal\u2192Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Surface\u219