nal module within the larger network.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Specify mineral surfaces for Strecker reaction (e.g., pyrite, clay minerals)\", \"Should ideally be embedded in longer pathways like P1 or P2\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_010\": 0.80, \"rxn_011\": 0.75, \"rxn_012\": 0.85},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.80,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.75,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.55,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.73,\n            \"feedback\": \"Short formose-glyoxylate route identical to P4. Same environmental cycling issue (Surface\u2192Surface\u2192Hydrothermal). Chemically reasonable but the backward environmental transition lowers confidence.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Same as P4\"]\n        }\n    ],\n    \"best_pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n    \"overall_confidence\": 0.84,\n    \"network_feedback\": \"This is a well-constructed synthesis network for prebiotic glycine formation. Key strengths: (1) Formaldehyde as a central hub molecule is chemically well-justified and connects hydrothermal carbon fixation to multiple surface pathways elegantly. (2) The dual terminal routes to glycine (Strecker/hydrolysis via aminoacetonitrile and reductive amination via glyoxylic acid) provide robust convergence. (3) The hydrothermal reactions appropriately specify mineral catalysts (greigite, magnetite, native iron). Key weaknesses: (1) The formate-to-formaldehyde reduction (rxn_003) is the most thermodynamically challenging step and needs better experimental support. (2) Surface reactions lack mineral catalyst specifications\u2014clay minerals, zeolites, or oxide surfaces should be named. (3) The glyoxylate pathway (rxn_012) is placed in