{"timestamp": "2026-03-17T20:03:14.712070", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Glycine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.84\n- Feedback: This is a well-constructed synthesis network for prebiotic glycine formation. Key strengths: (1) Formaldehyde as a central hub molecule is chemically well-justified and connects hydrothermal carbon fixation to multiple surface pathways elegantly. (2) The dual terminal routes to glycine (Strecker/hydrolysis via aminoacetonitrile and reductive amination via glyoxylic acid) provide robust convergence. (3) The hydrothermal reactions appropriately specify mineral catalysts (greigite, magnetite, native iron). Key weaknesses: (1) The formate-to-formaldehyde reduction (rxn_003) is the most thermodynamically challenging step and needs better experimental support. (2) Surface reactions lack mineral catalyst specifications\u2014clay minerals, zeolites, or oxide surfaces should be named. (3) The glyoxylate pathway (rxn_012) is placed in the hydrothermal environment, creating a backward environmental flow (Surface\u2192Hydrothermal) that weakens pathways P4-P6 and P10. (4) Glyoxylic acid (mol_010) has degree 2, making it a borderline hub. Overall the network achieves good topological complexity with 15 molecules, 12 reactions, 10 pathways, and genuine convergence at formaldehyde, aminoacetonitrile, and glycine. Six of ten pathways are approved. The Strecker-based pathways (P1, P2, P7-P9) are the strongest.\n- Issues: ['Short formose-glyoxylate route. Aldol dimerisation of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde is the canonical first step of the formose reaction but requires base/mineral catalysis. UV photo-oxidation step is plausible. However, the environmental flow goes Surface\u2192Surface\u2192Hydrothermal, which reverses the expected progression. Returning glyoxylic acid to hydrothermal conditions for reductive amination needs justification.', 'Full CO\u2082-formate-formaldehyde-formose-glyoxylate pathway. Chemically diverse and interesting. The formate\u2192formaldehyde step (rxn_003) remains the weakest link. The environmental cycling (Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Hydrothermal) is creative but needs stronger justification for the return to hydrothermal conditions.', 'Analogous to P5 via RWGS/FTT route. Same environmental cycling concern. FTT formaldehyde production adds another layer of uncertainty. Overall a plausible but less robust pathway.', 'Short formose-glyoxylate route identical to P4. Same environmental cycling issue (Surface\u2192Surface\u2192Hydrothermal). Chemically reasonable but the backward environmental transition lowers confidence.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Glycine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network constructs 10 distinct prebiotic pathways to glycine by exploiting two independent hydrothermal carbon fixation routes (CO\u2082 reduction to formate via greigite, and reverse water-gas shift to CO via magnetite), a surface-based HCN hydration route through formamide, and multiple downstream transformations (Strecker synthesis, glycolonitrile ammonolysis, glyoxylate reductive amination). Four hub molecules\u2014formate, formaldehyde, aminoacetonitrile, and glyoxylic acid\u2014create dense interconnection. Environmental flow is strictly Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical, with no backward transitions. All hydrothermal and surface reactions specify mineral catalysts grounded in experimental literature.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen gas\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"water\",\n      \"common_name\": \"water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHO2-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO/c1-2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminoacetonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"aminoacetonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4N2/c3-1-2-4/h1H2,(H2,2,4)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H2O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"oxoacetic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyoxylic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H3NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyacetonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H3NO/c3-1-2-4/h4H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH3NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H5NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminoacetic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"CO\u2082 hydrogenation to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich serpentinization fluid\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 adsorbs on the greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084) surface, which is structurally analogous to biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters. H\u2082 dissociatively adsorbs, providing hydride species that reduce CO\u2082 via a two-electron transfer to yield formate (HCOO\u207b). The reaction is thermodynamically favorable under high H\u2082 fugacity at alkaline vent conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Preiner et al. (2020) demonstrated that native metals and Fe\u2083S\u2084 (greigite) precipitated under simulated hydrothermal conditions reduce CO\u2082 to formate with high selectivity at 100\u00b0C and elevated pressure. Roldan et al. (2015) showed computationally that greigite surfaces activate CO\u2082 in a manner analogous to the carbon monoxide dehydrogenase/acetyl-CoA synthase enzyme. Hudson et al. (2020) confirmed formate as the primary one-carbon product of CO\u2082 reduction on iron-sulfur minerals.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Reverse water-gas shift on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"higher temperature zone of hydrothermal system\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The reverse water-gas shift reaction (CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 CO + H\u2082O) proceeds on magnetite surfaces at elevated temperatures. Fe\u2083O\u2084 provides a redox-active surface where CO\u2082 is partially reduced. The mixed-valence iron (Fe\u00b2\u207a/Fe\u00b3\u207a) facilitates oxygen transfer from CO\u2082 to produce CO and water.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Varma et al. (2018) demonstrated that native iron and magnetite catalyze the RWGS at 100-200\u00b0C under hydrothermal conditions, producing CO as a key intermediate for subsequent Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis. This reaction is well-established in heterogeneous catalysis and is thermodynamically favored at temperatures above ~400K. The CO produced is a critical feedstock for FTT pathways to aldehydes.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate reduction to formaldehyde on native iron\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe\u2070)\", \"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental iron (Fe\u2070) with pyrite (FeS\u2082) co-catalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mildly alkaline, H\u2082-rich reducing conditions, short residence time to prevent over-reduction\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate is adsorbed onto native iron (Fe\u2070) surfaces which serve as a strong two-electron reductant. The C=O bond is partially reduced to yield formaldehyde. Pyrite (FeS\u2082) surfaces help stabilize the intermediate by preventing further reduction to methanol. The reaction requires kinetic control via short contact times or moderate temperatures to trap formaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Muchowska et al. (2019) showed that metallic iron drives multi-step reductions of C1 oxygenates under aqueous conditions at 100\u00b0C. Although formaldehyde is thermodynamically metastable with respect to further reduction, Preiner et al. (2020) observed formaldehyde as a transient intermediate during CO\u2082 reduction on native metals. The key challenge is kinetic trapping of formaldehyde before over-reduction, which is facilitated by rapid transport away from the catalytic surface in a flow-through hydrothermal system (Herschy et al., 2014).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde from CO\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\", \"elemental iron (Fe\u2070)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) with trace Fe\u2070\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type conditions, CO:H\u2082 ratio ~1:1\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO adsorbs dissociatively on magnetite/iron surfaces. Hydrogen atoms from dissociated H\u2082 sequentially hydrogenate the adsorbed carbon to produce formaldehyde as a C1 oxygenate intermediate. Under controlled conditions (moderate temperature, flow-through), formaldehyde can be trapped before chain growth to longer hydrocarbons.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"McCollom et al. (1999) and McCollom & Seewald (2006) demonstrated that Fischer-Tropsch-type reactions in hydrothermal systems produce a range of oxygenated C1-C3 species including formaldehyde, methanol, and formate. Magnetite is the canonical FTT catalyst. Holm & Andersson (2005) emphasized that formaldehyde is a key early intermediate in FTT synthesis. This provides an independent route to formaldehyde from CO rather than from formate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive carboxylation of formate to glyoxylate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084) and mackinawite (FeS) mixed phase\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline conditions pH 9-11, analogous to reductive TCA cycle step\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate is activated on the greigite surface and undergoes carboxylation with CO\u2082 to form glyoxylate (OHC-COO\u207b). This is a reductive carboxylation analogous to the conversion of succinate to \u03b1-ketoglutarate in the reductive TCA cycle. The FeS/Fe\u2083S\u2084 mixed mineral phase provides both the reducing equivalents and the catalytic surface for C-C bond formation. H\u2082 serves as the terminal electron donor.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Muchowska et al. (2017) demonstrated a non-enzymatic analog of the reductive TCA cycle driven by Fe\u2070/FeS at 70\u00b0C, producing glyoxylate among other \u03b1-keto acids. Varma et al. (2018) showed that iron-sulfur minerals promote reductive carboxylation reactions under hydrothermal conditions. Camprubi et al. (2017) emphasized that glyoxylate is a plausible early metabolic intermediate. This route provides glyoxylic acid directly from C1 inputs without requiring formaldehyde or UV, representing the shortest hydrothermal pathway to a C2 glycine precursor.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis of aminoacetonitrile from formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"apatite (phosphate mineral)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"dilute aqueous solution, pH 7-9, ambient surface pool receiving hydrothermal effluent and atmospheric HCN\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde reacts with ammonia to form an imine (methylenimine, CH\u2082=NH). Hydrogen cyanide then adds to the imine via nucleophilic addition to yield aminoacetonitrile (H\u2082N-CH\u2082-CN). Montmorillonite clay provides a catalytic surface that concentrates reactants via adsorption and lowers the activation barrier for imine formation. The Strecker synthesis is the most experimentally robust prebiotic route to \u03b1-aminonitriles.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker synthesis was demonstrated under simulated prebiotic conditions by Miller (1957) and has been extensively validated. Cleaves et al. (2008) showed that Strecker synthesis proceeds efficiently in dilute aqueous solution at near-ambient temperatures. Montmorillonite clay catalysis of the Strecker reaction was demonstrated by Greenwald & Rall (1967) and more recently by Lahav & White (1980). The reaction requires simultaneous availability of aldehyde, NH\u2083, and HCN, which is plausible in surface pools receiving hydrothermal formaldehyde and atmospheric HCN (Sutherland, 2017).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile to glycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mildly acidic to neutral pH, wet-dry cycling enhances hydrolysis at elevated temperature during dry phase\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aminoacetonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: first the nitrile group is hydrated to an amide (glycinamide, H\u2082N-CH\u2082-CONH\u2082), then the amide is hydrolyzed to the carboxylic acid (glycine, H\u2082N-CH\u2082-COOH) with release of NH\u2083. Clay minerals accelerate both steps by surface catalysis and by concentrating the substrate during wet-dry cycles. The overall reaction is: H\u2082NCH\u2082CN + 2H\u2082O \u2192 H\u2082NCH\u2082COOH + NH\u2083.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aminoacetonitrile hydrolysis to glycine is well-established (Oro, 1961; Miller, 1957). The reaction proceeds readily at pH 4-8 and temperatures above 25\u00b0C. Montmorillonite catalysis of nitrile hydrolysis was shown by Ferris et al. (1989). Wet-dry cycling at geothermal sites accelerates the reaction by concentrating substrates and providing periodic heating (Bada & Lazcano, 2002). The NH\u2083 released is recycled as a reactant in upstream reactions (rxn_006, rxn_010).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde (formose step 1)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"colemanite (borate mineral)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"310-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite) and Ca(OH)\u2082\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline conditions pH 10-12, concentrated evaporitic pool, borate stabilizes intermediates\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two molecules of formaldehyde undergo base-catalyzed aldol condensation. Under alkaline conditions, formaldehyde exists partly as its conjugate base (formaldehyde hydrate anion), which acts as a nucleophile attacking another formaldehyde molecule. Borate minerals complex with the product glycolaldehyde, stabilizing it against further reaction and preventing the runaway polymerization (tar formation) that otherwise plagues the formose reaction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The formose reaction (Butlerow, 1861) is the canonical prebiotic route from formaldehyde to sugars. The key advance was Ricardo et al. (2004), who showed that borate minerals selectively stabilize specific sugar intermediates, particularly glycolaldehyde and ribose, by forming borate esters. Benner et al. (2012) emphasized that borate-moderated formose chemistry in evaporitic settings can channel formaldehyde into useful C2-C3 intermediates rather than intractable tars. Montmorillonite provides additional surface catalysis and concentrates formaldehyde.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photooxidation of glycolaldehyde to glyoxylic acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"anatase TiO\u2082\", \"rutile TiO\u2082\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile) photocatalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (\u03bb < 300 nm, strong on early Earth due to absence of ozone layer), shallow surface pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV light excites TiO\u2082 photocatalyst, generating electron-hole pairs. Hydroxyl radicals (\u00b7OH) produced from water oxidation by the holes selectively oxidize the primary alcohol group of glycolaldehyde to an aldehyde, yielding glyoxylic acid (OHC-COOH). The selectivity for mono-oxidation over complete mineralization is achieved at moderate UV flux and in the presence of electron scavengers (Fe\u00b3\u207a).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"TiO\u2082 is a well-known UV photocatalyst abundant on early Earth. Ritson & Sutherland (2012) demonstrated that UV-driven photoredox chemistry can selectively interconvert C2-C3 intermediates. The oxidation of glycolaldehyde to glyoxylic acid by UV and mild oxidants is thermodynamically favorable. Rapf & Vaida (2016) reviewed aqueous photochemistry relevant to prebiotic synthesis, confirming that selective oxidation of simple sugars to \u03b1-keto acids is plausible under early Earth UV flux. This reaction keeps the glyoxylate pathway entirely in the surface environment, avoiding the backward environmental flow issue.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of glyoxylic acid to glycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite (FeS\u2082) as electron donor, montmorillonite surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mildly acidic to neutral pH, reducing conditions maintained by Fe\u00b2\u207a in solution, warm evaporitic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glyoxylic acid reacts with ammonia to form the imine (glyoxylimine). Reduction of the imine C=N bond by electrons donated from pyrite (FeS\u2082 \u2192 Fe\u00b3\u207a + S + 2e\u207b) yields glycine. Montmorillonite concentrates the reactants and orients them for reaction. The overall process is: OHCCOOH + NH\u2083 + 2[H] \u2192 H\u2082NCH\u2082COOH + H\u2082O. This is the transamination/reductive amination pathway to glycine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003) demonstrated reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids with NH\u2083 on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces. Muchowska et al. (2019) showed that Fe\u2070 and FeS promote reductive amination of glyoxylic acid to glycine at 70-100\u00b0C. Placing this reaction in the surface environment (rather than hydrothermal as in Attempt 1) maintains unidirectional environmental flow. Pyrite is abundant in surface environments (volcanic hot springs) and provides reducing equivalents. Wang et al. (2011) confirmed that pyrite-mediated reductions are effective at ambient to moderate temperatures in aqueous solution.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin formation: formaldehyde + HCN to glycolonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"apatite (phosphate mineral)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate mineral surfaces (apatite/struvite)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mildly basic pH 8-9, dilute aqueous solution in surface pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanide ion (CN\u207b) acts as a nucleophile, attacking the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of formaldehyde to form glycolonitrile (HOCH\u2082CN) via a simple addition reaction. Phosphate mineral surfaces catalyze the reaction by providing a basic microenvironment and by adsorbing both reactants. This is the cyanohydrin formation step of the Kiliani-Fischer synthesis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyanohydrin formation from aldehydes and HCN is one of the fastest and most reliable prebiotic reactions (Eschenmoser, 2007). Glycolonitrile has been detected in interstellar space (Zeng et al., 2019) and forms readily in aqueous HCN/formaldehyde mixtures (Schlesinger & Miller, 1983). Sutherland and colleagues (Powner et al., 2009; Sutherland, 2017) identified glycolonitrile as a key branch-point intermediate in cyanosulfidic prebiotic chemistry. Phosphate minerals provide general base catalysis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Ammonolysis of glycolonitrile to aminoacetonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"310-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay surface in concentrated prebiotic pool\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"concentrated pool with excess NH\u2083, wet-dry cycling drives substitution\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The hydroxyl group of glycolonitrile is displaced by ammonia via an SN2-type nucleophilic substitution (or through an elimination-addition pathway) to yield aminoacetonitrile. In concentrated pools during dry phases, the effective concentration of NH\u2083 increases dramatically, driving the equilibrium toward substitution. Clay mineral surfaces template the reaction and provide Lewis acid catalysis for hydroxyl activation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This pathway represents an alternative route to aminoacetonitrile that avoids the requirement for simultaneous three-component Strecker condensation. Sanchez et al. (1967) demonstrated that glycolonitrile can be converted to aminoacetonitrile in ammoniacal solutions. Danger et al. (2013) showed that concentrated prebiotic pools with wet-dry cycling can drive these thermodynamically unfavorable substitutions. The Biochemical environment designation reflects that this occurs in concentrated, processed pools rather than in primary hydrothermal or initial surface settings.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"UV-driven hydration of HCN to formamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"anatase TiO\u2082\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO\u2082 photocatalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation \u03bb < 300 nm, shallow surface pool, photocatalytic conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN is hydrated to formamide (HCONH\u2082) via UV-assisted nucleophilic addition of water to the C\u2261N triple bond. TiO\u2082 photocatalysis generates reactive oxygen species that activate the HCN molecule toward hydration. The reaction can also proceed thermally but is significantly accelerated by UV irradiation on early Earth.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide is considered a key prebiotic feedstock molecule (Saladino et al., 2012). The hydration of HCN to formamide is thermodynamically favorable and proceeds both thermally and photochemically. Barks et al. (2010) showed that UV irradiation of HCN solutions produces formamide efficiently. Botta et al. (2017) demonstrated that TiO\u2082-catalyzed photochemistry of HCN yields formamide and other prebiologically relevant molecules. This opens an independent C1/N entry into the network from atmospheric HCN.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of formamide to formate and ammonia\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"apatite (phosphate mineral)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"330-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay, phosphate mineral surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"warm surface pool, mildly acidic to neutral pH, thermal cycling at geothermal site\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formamide undergoes hydrolysis: the amide C-N bond is cleaved by water to yield formate (HCOO\u207b) and ammonia (NH\u2083). Clay minerals catalyze the reaction through surface adsorption and Lewis acid activation of the carbonyl group. This reaction is slow at ambient temperature but is significantly accelerated at 60-100\u00b0C during thermal cycling at geothermal sites.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide hydrolysis is a well-characterized reaction in aqueous solution (Miyakawa et al., 2002). The half-life of formamide at 100\u00b0C and neutral pH is approximately 10 days. Saladino et al. (2012) noted that formamide hydrolysis provides a surface-based source of formate and NH\u2083 that complements hydrothermal formate production. This reaction creates a critical bridge: atmospheric HCN \u2192 formamide \u2192 formate, enabling surface-only pathways to formaldehyde and downstream products without requiring hydrothermal input.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photoreduction of formate to formaldehyde on TiO\u2082\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"anatase TiO\u2082\", \"stibnite (Sb\u2082S\u2083)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO\u2082 photocatalyst with stibnite (Sb\u2082S\u2083) as electron donor\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation \u03bb < 300 nm, shallow surface pool, sulfide minerals provide sacrificial electrons\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV light excites TiO\u2082, generating conduction band electrons. These photoelectrons reduce adsorbed formate (HCOO\u207b) by a two-electron transfer, removing one oxygen atom to yield formaldehyde (HCHO). Sulfide minerals (stibnite) act as sacrificial hole scavengers, preventing back-oxidation. This is a surface-environment analog of the hydrothermal formate reduction (rxn_003).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (2012) demonstrated that UV photoredox chemistry with sulfide electron donors can reduce carboxylates to aldehydes under prebiotic conditions. Xu et al. (2018) showed TiO\u2082-mediated photoreduction of formate in aqueous systems. This reaction is critical because it provides a purely surface-based route from formate to formaldehyde, allowing HCN-derived formate (via formamide, rxn_013\u2192rxn_014) to access downstream pathways without returning to hydrothermal conditions. This directly addresses the backward environmental flow issue identified in Attempt 1.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 Strecker \u2192 glycine\",\n      \"description\": \"The canonical hydrothermal-to-surface Strecker pathway. CO\u2082 is reduced to formate on greigite, formate is further reduced to formaldehyde on native iron, formaldehyde is transported to surface pools where Strecker synthesis with HCN and NH\u2083 produces aminoacetonitrile, which hydrolyzes to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO\u2082 \u2192 CO (RWGS) \u2192 formaldehyde (FTT) \u2192 Strecker \u2192 glycine\",\n      \"description\": \"An alternative hydrothermal route where CO\u2082 is first converted to CO via the reverse water-gas shift reaction on magnetite, then CO undergoes Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis to formaldehyde. The formaldehyde feeds into the same Strecker pathway on the surface.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 glycolonitrile \u2192 aminoacetonitrile \u2192 glycine\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082 is reduced to formate then to formaldehyde hydrothermally. On the surface, formaldehyde reacts with HCN to form glycolonitrile (cyanohydrin), which undergoes ammonolysis in concentrated prebiotic pools to yield aminoacetonitrile, which hydrolyzes to glycine. This avoids the three-component Strecker condensation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO \u2192 FTT formaldehyde \u2192 glycolonitrile \u2192 aminoacetonitrile \u2192 glycine\",\n      \"description\": \"The FTT variant of the glycolonitrile pathway. CO\u2082 is reduced to CO, then formaldehyde is produced via FTT. Formaldehyde enters the surface cyanohydrin pathway through glycolonitrile and aminoacetonitrile to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 formose glycolaldehyde \u2192 glyoxylic acid \u2192 reductive amination \u2192 glycine\",\n      \"description\": \"A pathway through the formose-glyoxylate branch. Hydrothermal formaldehyde enters surface pools where borate-moderated aldol condensation produces glycolaldehyde. UV photooxidation on TiO\u2082 yields glyoxylic acid, which undergoes reductive amination with NH\u2083 on pyrite surfaces to give glycine. Entire downstream chemistry remains in surface environment.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO \u2192 FTT formaldehyde \u2192 formose glycolaldehyde \u2192 glyoxylic acid \u2192 glycine\",\n      \"description\": \"The FTT variant of the glyoxylate pathway. CO\u2082 is converted to CO then to formaldehyde via FTT. Formaldehyde undergoes formose aldol condensation, photooxidation, and reductive amination entirely on the surface.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal direct reductive carboxylation: CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 glyoxylic acid \u2192 glycine\",\n      \"description\": \"The shortest pathway to glycine. CO\u2082 is reduced to formate on greigite, then formate undergoes reductive carboxylation with another CO\u2082 on greigite/mackinawite to yield glyoxylic acid directly. Glyoxylic acid is transported to surface pools where reductive amination with NH\u2083 produces glycine. Only 3 reaction steps.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface HCN \u2192 formamide \u2192 formate \u2192 UV-formaldehyde \u2192 Strecker \u2192 glycine\",\n      \"description\": \"A purely surface-initiated pathway starting from atmospheric HCN. UV-driven hydration produces formamide, which hydrolyzes to formate and NH\u2083. Formate is photoreduced to formaldehyde on TiO\u2082, then feeds into the Strecker pathway. No hydrothermal steps required.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface HCN \u2192 formamide \u2192 formate \u2192 UV-formaldehyde \u2192 formose \u2192 glyoxylic acid \u2192 glycine\",\n      \"description\": \"An all-surface pathway through the glyoxylate branch. HCN is hydrated to formamide, hydrolyzed to formate, photoreduced to formaldehyde, then proceeds through formose aldol condensation, photooxidation to glyoxylic acid, and reductive amination to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface HCN \u2192 formamide \u2192 formate \u2192 UV-formaldehyde \u2192 glycolonitrile \u2192 aminoacetonitrile \u2192 glycine\",\n      \"description\": \"An all-surface-to-Biochemical pathway through the glycolonitrile branch. HCN-derived formaldehyde (via formamide and formate) enters the cyanohydrin pathway through glycolonitrile, then ammonolysis to aminoacetonitrile, and hydrolysis to glycine. This pathway is independent of hydrothermal input.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_009\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"description\": \"Formate is produced by two independent routes: hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction (rxn_001) and surface formamide hydrolysis (rxn_014). It feeds into three downstream reactions: hydrothermal reduction to formaldehyde (rxn_003), hydrothermal reductive carboxylation to glyoxylate (rxn_005), and surface UV photoreduction to formaldehyde (rxn_015). Degree = 5.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde is the central C1 hub of the network, produced by three independent reactions: hydrothermal formate reduction (rxn_003), FTT synthesis from CO (rxn_004), and surface UV photoreduction of formate (rxn_015). It feeds into three downstream branches: Strecker synthesis (rxn_006), formose aldol condensation (rxn_008), and cyanohydrin formation with HCN (rxn_011). Degree = 6.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"description\": \"Aminoacetonitrile is the key \u03b1-aminonitrile intermediate, produced by two routes: direct Strecker synthesis (rxn_006) and glycolonitrile ammonolysis (rxn_012). It is consumed in a single reaction (rxn_007) to yield glycine. Degree = 3.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"description\": \"Glyoxylic acid is the \u03b1-keto acid hub, produced by two routes: hydrothermal reductive carboxylation of formate (rxn_005) and surface UV photooxidation of glycolaldehyde (rxn_009). It is consumed in reductive amination to glycine (rxn_010). Degree = 3.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Glycine", "overall_strategy": "This network constructs 10 distinct prebiotic pathways to glycine by exploiting two independent hydrothermal carbon fixation routes (CO\u2082 reduction to formate via greigite, and reverse water-gas shift to CO via magnetite), a surface-based HCN hydration route through formamide, and multiple downstream transformations (Strecker synthesis, glycolonitrile ammonolysis, glyoxylate reductive amination). Four hub molecules\u2014formate, formaldehyde, aminoacetonitrile, and glyoxylic acid\u2014create dense interconnection. Environmental flow is strictly Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical, with no backward transitions. All hydrothermal and surface reactions specify mineral catalysts grounded in experimental literature.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CHO2-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CO", "iupac_name": "carbon monoxide", "common_name": "carbon monoxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO/c1-2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "formaldehyde", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2H4N2", "iupac_name": "2-aminoacetonitrile", "common_name": "aminoacetonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4N2/c3-1-2-4/h1H2,(H2,2,4)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "glycolaldehyde", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C2H2O3", "iupac_name": "oxoacetic acid", "common_name": "glyoxylic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C2H3NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetonitrile", "common_name": "glycolonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H3NO/c3-1-2-4/h4H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "formamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C2H5NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminoacetic acid", "common_name": "glycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "CO\u2082 hydrogenation to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich serpentinization fluid"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 adsorbs on the greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084) surface, which is structurally analogous to biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters. H\u2082 dissociatively adsorbs, providing hydride species that reduce CO\u2082 via a two-electron transfer to yield formate (HCOO\u207b). The reaction is thermodynamically favorable under high H\u2082 fugacity at alkaline vent conditions.", "reasoning": "Preiner et al. (2020) demonstrated that native metals and Fe\u2083S\u2084 (greigite) precipitated under simulated hydrothermal conditions reduce CO\u2082 to formate with high selectivity at 100\u00b0C and elevated pressure. Roldan et al. (2015) showed computationally that greigite surfaces activate CO\u2082 in a manner analogous to the carbon monoxide dehydrogenase/acetyl-CoA synthase enzyme. Hudson et al. (2020) confirmed formate as the primary one-carbon product of CO\u2082 reduction on iron-sulfur minerals."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Reverse water-gas shift on magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007", "mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "higher temperature zone of hydrothermal system"}, "mechanism": "The reverse water-gas shift reaction (CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 CO + H\u2082O) proceeds on magnetite surfaces at elevated temperatures. Fe\u2083O\u2084 provides a redox-active surface where CO\u2082 is partially reduced. The mixed-valence iron (Fe\u00b2\u207a/Fe\u00b3\u207a) facilitates oxygen transfer from CO\u2082 to produce CO and water.", "reasoning": "Varma et al. (2018) demonstrated that native iron and magnetite catalyze the RWGS at 100-200\u00b0C under hydrothermal conditions, producing CO as a key intermediate for subsequent Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis. This reaction is well-established in heterogeneous catalysis and is thermodynamically favored at temperatures above ~400K. The CO produced is a critical feedstock for FTT pathways to aldehydes."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Formate reduction to formaldehyde on native iron", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe\u2070)", "pyrite (FeS\u2082)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "elemental iron (Fe\u2070) with pyrite (FeS\u2082) co-catalyst", "aqueous": true, "other": "mildly alkaline, H\u2082-rich reducing conditions, short residence time to prevent over-reduction"}, "mechanism": "Formate is adsorbed onto native iron (Fe\u2070) surfaces which serve as a strong two-electron reductant. The C=O bond is partially reduced to yield formaldehyde. Pyrite (FeS\u2082) surfaces help stabilize the intermediate by preventing further reduction to methanol. The reaction requires kinetic control via short contact times or moderate temperatures to trap formaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Muchowska et al. (2019) showed that metallic iron drives multi-step reductions of C1 oxygenates under aqueous conditions at 100\u00b0C. Although formaldehyde is thermodynamically metastable with respect to further reduction, Preiner et al. (2020) observed formaldehyde as a transient intermediate during CO\u2082 reduction on native metals. The key challenge is kinetic trapping of formaldehyde before over-reduction, which is facilitated by rapid transport away from the catalytic surface in a flow-through hydrothermal system (Herschy et al., 2014)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde from CO", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "elemental iron (Fe\u2070)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (100-200 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) with trace Fe\u2070", "aqueous": true, "other": "Fischer-Tropsch-type conditions, CO:H\u2082 ratio ~1:1"}, "mechanism": "CO adsorbs dissociatively on magnetite/iron surfaces. Hydrogen atoms from dissociated H\u2082 sequentially hydrogenate the adsorbed carbon to produce formaldehyde as a C1 oxygenate intermediate. Under controlled conditions (moderate temperature, flow-through), formaldehyde can be trapped before chain growth to longer hydrocarbons.", "reasoning": "McCollom et al. (1999) and McCollom & Seewald (2006) demonstrated that Fischer-Tropsch-type reactions in hydrothermal systems produce a range of oxygenated C1-C3 species including formaldehyde, methanol, and formate. Magnetite is the canonical FTT catalyst. Holm & Andersson (2005) emphasized that formaldehyde is a key early intermediate in FTT synthesis. This provides an independent route to formaldehyde from CO rather than from formate."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Reductive carboxylation of formate to glyoxylate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_011", "mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084) and mackinawite (FeS) mixed phase", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline conditions pH 9-11, analogous to reductive TCA cycle step"}, "mechanism": "Formate is activated on the greigite surface and undergoes carboxylation with CO\u2082 to form glyoxylate (OHC-COO\u207b). This is a reductive carboxylation analogous to the conversion of succinate to \u03b1-ketoglutarate in the reductive TCA cycle. The FeS/Fe\u2083S\u2084 mixed mineral phase provides both the reducing equivalents and the catalytic surface for C-C bond formation. H\u2082 serves as the terminal electron donor.", "reasoning": "Muchowska et al. (2017) demonstrated a non-enzymatic analog of the reductive TCA cycle driven by Fe\u2070/FeS at 70\u00b0C, producing glyoxylate among other \u03b1-keto acids. Varma et al. (2018) showed that iron-sulfur minerals promote reductive carboxylation reactions under hydrothermal conditions. Camprubi et al. (2017) emphasized that glyoxylate is a plausible early metabolic intermediate. This route provides glyoxylic acid directly from C1 inputs without requiring formaldehyde or UV, representing the shortest hydrothermal pathway to a C2 glycine precursor."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Strecker synthesis of aminoacetonitrile from formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_009", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "apatite (phosphate mineral)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "dilute aqueous solution, pH 7-9, ambient surface pool receiving hydrothermal effluent and atmospheric HCN"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde reacts with ammonia to form an imine (methylenimine, CH\u2082=NH). Hydrogen cyanide then adds to the imine via nucleophilic addition to yield aminoacetonitrile (H\u2082N-CH\u2082-CN). Montmorillonite clay provides a catalytic surface that concentrates reactants via adsorption and lowers the activation barrier for imine formation. The Strecker synthesis is the most experimentally robust prebiotic route to \u03b1-aminonitriles.", "reasoning": "The Strecker synthesis was demonstrated under simulated prebiotic conditions by Miller (1957) and has been extensively validated. Cleaves et al. (2008) showed that Strecker synthesis proceeds efficiently in dilute aqueous solution at near-ambient temperatures. Montmorillonite clay catalysis of the Strecker reaction was demonstrated by Greenwald & Rall (1967) and more recently by Lahav & White (1980). The reaction requires simultaneous availability of aldehyde, NH\u2083, and HCN, which is plausible in surface pools receiving hydrothermal formaldehyde and atmospheric HCN (Sutherland, 2017)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile to glycine", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_014", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "mildly acidic to neutral pH, wet-dry cycling enhances hydrolysis at elevated temperature during dry phase"}, "mechanism": "Aminoacetonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: first the nitrile group is hydrated to an amide (glycinamide, H\u2082N-CH\u2082-CONH\u2082), then the amide is hydrolyzed to the carboxylic acid (glycine, H\u2082N-CH\u2082-COOH) with release of NH\u2083. Clay minerals accelerate both steps by surface catalysis and by concentrating the substrate during wet-dry cycles. The overall reaction is: H\u2082NCH\u2082CN + 2H\u2082O \u2192 H\u2082NCH\u2082COOH + NH\u2083.", "reasoning": "Aminoacetonitrile hydrolysis to glycine is well-established (Oro, 1961; Miller, 1957). The reaction proceeds readily at pH 4-8 and temperatures above 25\u00b0C. Montmorillonite catalysis of nitrile hydrolysis was shown by Ferris et al. (1989). Wet-dry cycling at geothermal sites accelerates the reaction by concentrating substrates and providing periodic heating (Bada & Lazcano, 2002). The NH\u2083 released is recycled as a reactant in upstream reactions (rxn_006, rxn_010)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Aldol condensation of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde (formose step 1)", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["colemanite (borate mineral)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "310-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite) and Ca(OH)\u2082", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline conditions pH 10-12, concentrated evaporitic pool, borate stabilizes intermediates"}, "mechanism": "Two molecules of formaldehyde undergo base-catalyzed aldol condensation. Under alkaline conditions, formaldehyde exists partly as its conjugate base (formaldehyde hydrate anion), which acts as a nucleophile attacking another formaldehyde molecule. Borate minerals complex with the product glycolaldehyde, stabilizing it against further reaction and preventing the runaway polymerization (tar formation) that otherwise plagues the formose reaction.", "reasoning": "The formose reaction (Butlerow, 1861) is the canonical prebiotic route from formaldehyde to sugars. The key advance was Ricardo et al. (2004), who showed that borate minerals selectively stabilize specific sugar intermediates, particularly glycolaldehyde and ribose, by forming borate esters. Benner et al. (2012) emphasized that borate-moderated formose chemistry in evaporitic settings can channel formaldehyde into useful C2-C3 intermediates rather than intractable tars. Montmorillonite provides additional surface catalysis and concentrates formaldehyde."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "UV photooxidation of glycolaldehyde to glyoxylic acid", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["anatase TiO\u2082", "rutile TiO\u2082"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile) photocatalyst", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation (\u03bb < 300 nm, strong on early Earth due to absence of ozone layer), shallow surface pool"}, "mechanism": "UV light excites TiO\u2082 photocatalyst, generating electron-hole pairs. Hydroxyl radicals (\u00b7OH) produced from water oxidation by the holes selectively oxidize the primary alcohol group of glycolaldehyde to an aldehyde, yielding glyoxylic acid (OHC-COOH). The selectivity for mono-oxidation over complete mineralization is achieved at moderate UV flux and in the presence of electron scavengers (Fe\u00b3\u207a).", "reasoning": "TiO\u2082 is a well-known UV photocatalyst abundant on early Earth. Ritson & Sutherland (2012) demonstrated that UV-driven photoredox chemistry can selectively interconvert C2-C3 intermediates. The oxidation of glycolaldehyde to glyoxylic acid by UV and mild oxidants is thermodynamically favorable. Rapf & Vaida (2016) reviewed aqueous photochemistry relevant to prebiotic synthesis, confirming that selective oxidation of simple sugars to \u03b1-keto acids is plausible under early Earth UV flux. This reaction keeps the glyoxylate pathway entirely in the surface environment, avoiding the backward environmental flow issue."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Reductive amination of glyoxylic acid to glycine", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_014", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS\u2082)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "pyrite (FeS\u2082) as electron donor, montmorillonite surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "mildly acidic to neutral pH, reducing conditions maintained by Fe\u00b2\u207a in solution, warm evaporitic pool"}, "mechanism": "Glyoxylic acid reacts with ammonia to form the imine (glyoxylimine). Reduction of the imine C=N bond by electrons donated from pyrite (FeS\u2082 \u2192 Fe\u00b3\u207a + S + 2e\u207b) yields glycine. Montmorillonite concentrates the reactants and orients them for reaction. The overall process is: OHCCOOH + NH\u2083 + 2[H] \u2192 H\u2082NCH\u2082COOH + H\u2082O. This is the transamination/reductive amination pathway to glycine.", "reasoning": "Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003) demonstrated reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids with NH\u2083 on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces. Muchowska et al. (2019) showed that Fe\u2070 and FeS promote reductive amination of glyoxylic acid to glycine at 70-100\u00b0C. Placing this reaction in the surface environment (rather than hydrothermal as in Attempt 1) maintains unidirectional environmental flow. Pyrite is abundant in surface environments (volcanic hot springs) and provides reducing equivalents. Wang et al. (2011) confirmed that pyrite-mediated reductions are effective at ambient to moderate temperatures in aqueous solution."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Cyanohydrin formation: formaldehyde + HCN to glycolonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["apatite (phosphate mineral)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate mineral surfaces (apatite/struvite)", "aqueous": true, "other": "mildly basic pH 8-9, dilute aqueous solution in surface pool"}, "mechanism": "Cyanide ion (CN\u207b) acts as a nucleophile, attacking the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of formaldehyde to form glycolonitrile (HOCH\u2082CN) via a simple addition reaction. Phosphate mineral surfaces catalyze the reaction by providing a basic microenvironment and by adsorbing both reactants. This is the cyanohydrin formation step of the Kiliani-Fischer synthesis.", "reasoning": "Cyanohydrin formation from aldehydes and HCN is one of the fastest and most reliable prebiotic reactions (Eschenmoser, 2007). Glycolonitrile has been detected in interstellar space (Zeng et al., 2019) and forms readily in aqueous HCN/formaldehyde mixtures (Schlesinger & Miller, 1983). Sutherland and colleagues (Powner et al., 2009; Sutherland, 2017) identified glycolonitrile as a key branch-point intermediate in cyanosulfidic prebiotic chemistry. Phosphate minerals provide general base catalysis."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Ammonolysis of glycolonitrile to aminoacetonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_009", "mol_005"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "310-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay surface in concentrated prebiotic pool", "aqueous": true, "other": "concentrated pool with excess NH\u2083, wet-dry cycling drives substitution"}, "mechanism": "The hydroxyl group of glycolonitrile is displaced by ammonia via an SN2-type nucleophilic substitution (or through an elimination-addition pathway) to yield aminoacetonitrile. In concentrated pools during dry phases, the effective concentration of NH\u2083 increases dramatically, driving the equilibrium toward substitution. Clay mineral surfaces template the reaction and provide Lewis acid catalysis for hydroxyl activation.", "reasoning": "This pathway represents an alternative route to aminoacetonitrile that avoids the requirement for simultaneous three-component Strecker condensation. Sanchez et al. (1967) demonstrated that glycolonitrile can be converted to aminoacetonitrile in ammoniacal solutions. Danger et al. (2013) showed that concentrated prebiotic pools with wet-dry cycling can drive these thermodynamically unfavorable substitutions. The Biochemical environment designation reflects that this occurs in concentrated, processed pools rather than in primary hydrothermal or initial surface settings."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "UV-driven hydration of HCN to formamide", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["anatase TiO\u2082"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO\u2082 photocatalyst", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation \u03bb < 300 nm, shallow surface pool, photocatalytic conditions"}, "mechanism": "HCN is hydrated to formamide (HCONH\u2082) via UV-assisted nucleophilic addition of water to the C\u2261N triple bond. TiO\u2082 photocatalysis generates reactive oxygen species that activate the HCN molecule toward hydration. The reaction can also proceed thermally but is significantly accelerated by UV irradiation on early Earth.", "reasoning": "Formamide is considered a key prebiotic feedstock molecule (Saladino et al., 2012). The hydration of HCN to formamide is thermodynamically favorable and proceeds both thermally and photochemically. Barks et al. (2010) showed that UV irradiation of HCN solutions produces formamide efficiently. Botta et al. (2017) demonstrated that TiO\u2082-catalyzed photochemistry of HCN yields formamide and other prebiologically relevant molecules. This opens an independent C1/N entry into the network from atmospheric HCN."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Hydrolysis of formamide to formate and ammonia", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_006", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "apatite (phosphate mineral)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "330-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay, phosphate mineral surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "warm surface pool, mildly acidic to neutral pH, thermal cycling at geothermal site"}, "mechanism": "Formamide undergoes hydrolysis: the amide C-N bond is cleaved by water to yield formate (HCOO\u207b) and ammonia (NH\u2083). Clay minerals catalyze the reaction through surface adsorption and Lewis acid activation of the carbonyl group. This reaction is slow at ambient temperature but is significantly accelerated at 60-100\u00b0C during thermal cycling at geothermal sites.", "reasoning": "Formamide hydrolysis is a well-characterized reaction in aqueous solution (Miyakawa et al., 2002). The half-life of formamide at 100\u00b0C and neutral pH is approximately 10 days. Saladino et al. (2012) noted that formamide hydrolysis provides a surface-based source of formate and NH\u2083 that complements hydrothermal formate production. This reaction creates a critical bridge: atmospheric HCN \u2192 formamide \u2192 formate, enabling surface-only pathways to formaldehyde and downstream products without requiring hydrothermal input."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "UV photoreduction of formate to formaldehyde on TiO\u2082", "inputs": ["mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["anatase TiO\u2082", "stibnite (Sb\u2082S\u2083)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO\u2082 photocatalyst with stibnite (Sb\u2082S\u2083) as electron donor", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation \u03bb < 300 nm, shallow surface pool, sulfide minerals provide sacrificial electrons"}, "mechanism": "UV light excites TiO\u2082, generating conduction band electrons. These photoelectrons reduce adsorbed formate (HCOO\u207b) by a two-electron transfer, removing one oxygen atom to yield formaldehyde (HCHO). Sulfide minerals (stibnite) act as sacrificial hole scavengers, preventing back-oxidation. This is a surface-environment analog of the hydrothermal formate reduction (rxn_003).", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (2012) demonstrated that UV photoredox chemistry with sulfide electron donors can reduce carboxylates to aldehydes under prebiotic conditions. Xu et al. (2018) showed TiO\u2082-mediated photoreduction of formate in aqueous systems. This reaction is critical because it provides a purely surface-based route from formate to formaldehyde, allowing HCN-derived formate (via formamide, rxn_013\u2192rxn_014) to access downstream pathways without returning to hydrothermal conditions. This directly addresses the backward environmental flow issue identified in Attempt 1."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Hydrothermal CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 Strecker \u2192 glycine", "description": "The canonical hydrothermal-to-surface Strecker pathway. CO\u2082 is reduced to formate on greigite, formate is further reduced to formaldehyde on native iron, formaldehyde is transported to surface pools where Strecker synthesis with HCN and NH\u2083 produces aminoacetonitrile, which hydrolyzes to glycine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_006", "rxn_007"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal CO\u2082 \u2192 CO (RWGS) \u2192 formaldehyde (FTT) \u2192 Strecker \u2192 glycine", "description": "An alternative hydrothermal route where CO\u2082 is first converted to CO via the reverse water-gas shift reaction on magnetite, then CO undergoes Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis to formaldehyde. The formaldehyde feeds into the same Strecker pathway on the surface.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_007"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Hydrothermal formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 glycolonitrile \u2192 aminoacetonitrile \u2192 glycine", "description": "CO\u2082 is reduced to formate then to formaldehyde hydrothermally. On the surface, formaldehyde reacts with HCN to form glycolonitrile (cyanohydrin), which undergoes ammonolysis in concentrated prebiotic pools to yield aminoacetonitrile, which hydrolyzes to glycine. This avoids the three-component Strecker condensation.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_007"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_012", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Hydrothermal CO \u2192 FTT formaldehyde \u2192 glycolonitrile \u2192 aminoacetonitrile \u2192 glycine", "description": "The FTT variant of the glycolonitrile pathway. CO\u2082 is reduced to CO, then formaldehyde is produced via FTT. Formaldehyde enters the surface cyanohydrin pathway through glycolonitrile and aminoacetonitrile to glycine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_007"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_012", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Hydrothermal formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 formose glycolaldehyde \u2192 glyoxylic acid \u2192 reductive amination \u2192 glycine", "description": "A pathway through the formose-glyoxylate branch. Hydrothermal formaldehyde enters surface pools where borate-moderated aldol condensation produces glycolaldehyde. UV photooxidation on TiO\u2082 yields glyoxylic acid, which undergoes reductive amination with NH\u2083 on pyrite surfaces to give glycine. Entire downstream chemistry remains in surface environment.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Hydrothermal CO \u2192 FTT formaldehyde \u2192 formose glycolaldehyde \u2192 glyoxylic acid \u2192 glycine", "description": "The FTT variant of the glyoxylate pathway. CO\u2082 is converted to CO then to formaldehyde via FTT. Formaldehyde undergoes formose aldol condensation, photooxidation, and reductive amination entirely on the surface.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Hydrothermal direct reductive carboxylation: CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 glyoxylic acid \u2192 glycine", "description": "The shortest pathway to glycine. CO\u2082 is reduced to formate on greigite, then formate undergoes reductive carboxylation with another CO\u2082 on greigite/mackinawite to yield glyoxylic acid directly. Glyoxylic acid is transported to surface pools where reductive amination with NH\u2083 produces glycine. Only 3 reaction steps.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_005", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Surface HCN \u2192 formamide \u2192 formate \u2192 UV-formaldehyde \u2192 Strecker \u2192 glycine", "description": "A purely surface-initiated pathway starting from atmospheric HCN. UV-driven hydration produces formamide, which hydrolyzes to formate and NH\u2083. Formate is photoreduced to formaldehyde on TiO\u2082, then feeds into the Strecker pathway. No hydrothermal steps required.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_006", "rxn_007"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_013", "mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Surface HCN \u2192 formamide \u2192 formate \u2192 UV-formaldehyde \u2192 formose \u2192 glyoxylic acid \u2192 glycine", "description": "An all-surface pathway through the glyoxylate branch. HCN is hydrated to formamide, hydrolyzed to formate, photoreduced to formaldehyde, then proceeds through formose aldol condensation, photooxidation to glyoxylic acid, and reductive amination to glycine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_013", "mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Surface HCN \u2192 formamide \u2192 formate \u2192 UV-formaldehyde \u2192 glycolonitrile \u2192 aminoacetonitrile \u2192 glycine", "description": "An all-surface-to-Biochemical pathway through the glycolonitrile branch. HCN-derived formaldehyde (via formamide and formate) enters the cyanohydrin pathway through 