 (3 steps)\n  - P7: HCN-formamide \u2192 NH\u2083 supplemented Strecker pathway (5 steps)\n  - P8: HCN-formamide \u2192 NH\u2083 supplemented reductive amination pathway (4 steps)\n  - P9: Direct surface Strecker synthesis from delivered small molecules (3 steps)\n  - P10: Direct surface formose-glyoxylate reductive amination from delivered HCHO (3 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_006, mol_008, mol_010, mol_013\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 5\n\n\nPlease evaluate the network and respond with JSON:\n{\n    \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"<id>\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.85, ...},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"environmental_progression\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"target_achievement\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"feedback\": \"<pathway-specific feedback>\",\n            \"approved\": <true if confidence >= 0.8>,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_ids with issues\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"improvements\"]\n        }\n    ],\n    \"best_pathway_id\": \"<id of best pathway>\",\n    \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n    \"network_feedback\": \"<overall assessment>\",\n    \"approved\": <true if any pathway approved>,\n    \"hub_quality\": <0.0-1.0>,\n    \"convergence_quality\": <0.0-1.0>\n}\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.60,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.90\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.82,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.90,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.95,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.92,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.88,\n      \"feedback\": \"Strong Strecker pathway with full Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Biochemical progression. The weakest step is rxn_003 (formate\u2192formaldehyde on native iron), which is thermodynamically uphill and has limited experimental support. The Strecker core (rxn_007\u2013009) is very well established prebiotically. Greigite-catalysed CO\u2082 reduction is well supported by Roldan et al. and Preiner et al.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Consider whether awaruite (Ni\u2083Fe) or other alloy catalysts might improve rxn_003 feasibility\", \"Specify pH and temperature conditions for formate reduction\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.65,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.90\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.80,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.88,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.95,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.92,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.86,\n      \"feedback\": \"RWGS followed by FTT formaldehyde synthesis feeds into the Strecker pathway. rxn_004 is the bottleneck: formaldehyde is a transient FTT intermediate that is typically further reduced to methanol on magnetite surfaces. Trapping formaldehyde at useful concentrations is challenging but not implausible at rapid quenching/dilution near vent mixing zones.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Address formaldehyde stability and quenching mechanisms in FTT synthesis\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.60,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.75,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.70,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.85\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.72,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.82,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.93,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.82,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.78,\n      \"feedback\": \"The formose-glyoxylate branch is creative but has two moderate-feasibility steps. rxn_010 (formose self-condensation to glycolaldehyde) typically requires alkaline conditions and a catalyst like Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate minerals \u2013 the network should specify this. rxn_011 (UV photooxidation selectivity) may yield mixed products. rxn_003 remains the upstream bottleneck.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Specify borate or Ca(OH)\u2082 mineral catalyst for rxn_010\", \"Address selectivity of UV photooxidation in rxn_011\", \"Consider direct glyoxylate production from HCN/formaldehyde as alternative\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.65,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.75,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.70,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.85\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.72,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.80,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.93,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.82,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.77,\n      \"feedback\": \"Similar to P3 but uses RWGS-FTT front-end. Accumulates moderate-feasibility steps (rxn_004, rxn_010, rxn_011) making the overall pathway less reliable than the Strecker branches.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Same improvements as P3\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.60,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.75\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.75,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.80,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.60,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.78,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.73,\n      \"feedback\": \"Entirely hydrothermal pathway (no Surface or Biochemical stages). Inspired by Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user carbonylation chemistry. Lacks the environmental progression expected in the network design. rxn_013 combines HCHO + CO + NH\u2083 in a single step on FeNiS, which has some experimental support but the specific combination to produce glycine directly is less well-documented than the Strecker or reductive amination routes. rxn_003 remains a bottleneck.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Strengthen literature support for rxn_013 mechanism\", \"Consider whether glycine produced hydrothermally could still feed into biochemical concentration/polymerization steps\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.65,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.75\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.75,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.82,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.55,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.78,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.72,\n      \"feedback\": \"Shortest pathway (3 steps), entirely hydrothermal. Elegantly simple but lacks environmental progression. CO is produced alongside HCHO via FTT, and both are co-consumed in rxn_013, which is mechanistically plausible but difficult to validate. The lack of Surface/Biochemical stages weakens environmental scoring.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Add a downstream surface or biochemical concentration step to improve environmental flow\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.90\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.86,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.78,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.70,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.88,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.80,\n      \"feedback\": \"HCN-formamide hydrolysis supplies NH\u2083 and formate to the Strecker branch. Chemically sound individual steps; formamide hydrolysis on clay is well-supported (Saladino et al.). However, this pathway starts at Surface and misses Hydrothermal front-end generation of HCHO, which must be supplied from another pathway. The NH\u2083-supplementation role is valuable for the network but the pathway alone is incomplete without HCHO source.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Clarify that HCHO for rxn_007 must be imported from hydrothermal branches\", \"Could specify TiO\u2082 or ZnS mineral photocatalyst for rxn_005\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.85\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.82,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.68,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.65,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.80,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.72,\n      \"feedback\": \"Supplies NH\u2083 from formamide hydrolysis to the reductive amination branch. Coherence is weaker because glyoxylic acid (mol_013) must be sourced from the formose-photooxidation branch (P3/P4), and Fe\u00b2\u207a source is assumed. The pathway itself is more of a supplementary feeder than a standalone route.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Explicitly connect to glyoxylic acid source pathways\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.90\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.92,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.85,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.65,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.83,\n      \"feedback\": \"The chemically strongest pathway \u2013 the classical Strecker synthesis is the single most-validated prebiotic glycine route (Miller 1957, Peltzer & Bada 1978). Only Surface\u2192Surface\u2192Biochemical environmental progression; no hydrothermal front-end. Assumes all starting materials (HCHO, NH\u2083, HCN) are delivered exogenously or from other branches.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Could add mineral catalyst specification for Strecker step (e.g., montmorillonite)\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.75,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.70,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.85\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.73,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.72,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.65,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.78,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.70,\n      \"feedback\": \"Short surface-to-biochemical pathway via formose and photooxidation. Chemical feasibility is limited by selectivity issues in both rxn_010 and rxn_011. Formose reaction typically produces a complex mixture; glycolaldehyde selectivity requires borate stabilization. Photooxidation selectivity for glyoxylic acid over other products is uncertain.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Add borate minerals to rxn_010 for glycolaldehyde selectivity\", \"Provide evidence for photooxidation selectivity in rxn_011\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.84,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"This is a well-designed, convergent prebiotic synthesis network for glycine with strong topology and multiple redundant pathways. Key strengths: (1) Formaldehyde serves as an excellent hub with degree 5, connecting hydrothermal carbon fixation to both Strecker and glyoxylate branches. (2) The Strecker pathway core (rxn_007\u2192008\u2192009) is extremely well-established prebiotically. (3) Multiple independent hydrothermal front-ends (greigite CO\u2082 reduction, RWGS, FTT) provide robustness. (4) Environmental flow is well-maintained with clear Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Biochemical progression in the main pathways. Key weaknesses: (1) Two of four declared hub molecules (aminoacetonitrile, glyoxylic acid) have degree 2 and do not truly function as hubs. (2) The formate-to-formaldehyde reduction (rxn_003) and FTT formaldehyde capture (rxn_004) are the principal thermodynamic bottlenecks. (3) The formose-photooxidation branch (rxn_010\u2192011) has selectivity concerns that are not adequately addressed. (4) Mineral catalysts are not specified for all surface reactions (rxn_010 lacks mineral specification). (5) Literature citations are implied but not explicitly provided in reaction descriptions. Despite these issues, the network is chemically plausible, topologically sound, and successfully generates glycine through multiple convergent routes. The Strecker branch (P1, P2, P9) is the strongest component of the network.\",\n  \"approved\": true,\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.74,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.85\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_001": 0.9, "rxn_003": 0.6, "rxn_007": 0.95, "rxn_008": 0.9, "rxn_009": 0.9}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.82, "pathway_coherence": 0.9, "environmental_progression": 0.95, "target_achievement": 0.92, "overall_confidence": 0.88, "feedback": "Strong Strecker pathway with full Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Biochemical progression. The weakest step is rxn_003 (formate\u2192formaldehyde on native iron), which is thermodynamically uphill and has limited experimental support. The Strecker core (rxn_007\u2013009) is very well established prebiotically. Greigite-catalysed CO\u2082 reduction is well supported by Roldan et al. and Preiner et al.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_003"], "suggestions": ["Consider whether awaruite (Ni\u2083Fe) or other alloy catalysts might improve rxn_003 feasibility", "Specify pH and tempe